              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f , g \colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}Bx]]></fr:tex> be two dependent functions. A <html:em><html:strong>homotopy</html:strong></html:em> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex>, writing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\colon  f \sim  g]]></fr:tex> is given by a dependent function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}fx=gx]]></fr:tex>. We shall write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{f}\colon  f \sim  f]]></fr:tex> for the <html:em><html:strong>identity homotopy</html:strong></html:em> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{f}x:\equiv  \mathsf {refl}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
